It stood as title probably to the philosophie poem of Xenophanes, certainly to that of Parmeni- des, and the most important one of Empedocles. Empedocles' περὶ φύσεως both furnished a model and gave inspiration to our poet, who in several places shows traces of its influence. See 1, 716 et seq, and nn. Epicurus also left a treatise in thirty-seven books having the same title. See Diog. Laert. 10, 17, 27. Fragments oi it are extant in the work of Philodemus, deeiphered from the eharred rolls discovered at Herculaneum. Moreover, prior to Lucretius, Amafinius set forth in barbarous Latin the physical doctrines of Epicurus, though under what title or titles is not known.
